Use conditional compilation or the MAUI platform-specific `AddTransient`/`AddSingleton` pattern:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.IosNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under `Platforms/<platform>/` and is only compiled for that target. This won't break on other platforms because the preprocessor directives exclude irrelevant code at build time.

**Alternative** — if you prefer no `#if` directives, use partial classes or the `Platforms/` folder convention with `<TargetFramework>`-scoped file includes in your `.csproj`, then register a single concrete class name that resolves per-platform:

```xml
<!-- In .csproj, each platform folder is already conditionally included by default -->
```

```csharp
// Shared interface
public interface INotificationService { void Show(string title, string message); }

// Platforms/Android/NotificationService.cs  (compiled only on Android)
// Platforms/iOS/NotificationService.cs      (compiled only on iOS)
// Platforms/Windows/NotificationService.cs  (compiled only on Windows)
// All use:  public partial class NotificationService : INotificationService

// MauiProgram.cs — no #if needed
builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, NotificationService>();
```

The **partial-class approach** is cleaner for larger projects; the **`#if` approach** is simpler for quick setups.
